i agree.  testing should be made as easy as possible.  it will only help 
the adoption of junit, especially among new users.  i understand the value 
of testing, but sometimes i ask myself, &quot;is it worth it?&quot;when my test case 
code is longer than the actual implementation method that i&#39;m testing. 
just as we want to make our &quot;regular&quot; code easy to maintain, so should we 
the &quot;test&quot; code.

is there any type of proposal/voting mechanism in place for adopting new 
features to junit?  maybe something similar to jcp/jsr?  there could be a 
brief description of the proposed feature (e.g. like in my first email), 
with a brief description and sample usage.  these descriptions could be 
placed on the junit.org website and votes could be taken over the course of 
2/3/4 weeks (perhaps via the yahoogroups for quick/easy polling, and for 
recording of user&#39;s email to prevent duplicate votes).

in the meantime, if one wants to extend the functionality of the Assert 
class, given that all the methods are static, would be simply have to 
create our own class with static methods, and for existing assertXXX 
methods, provide calls to the corresponding methods in the Assert class 
(kind of like a decorator class does)?

thank you.





At 14:41 02/04/05 -0800, you wrote:
&gt;A few more methods in the assert class will not affect the extensibility 
&gt;of JUnit. Nor will it make JUnit any more difficult to understand. But it 
&gt;will enable new JUnit users to have more utilities at their fingertips. I 
&gt;think that most users are confused initially when they come to JUnit 
&gt;because it doesn&#39;t do a whole lot. Personally, I don&#39;t care a whole lot 
&gt;for my own use, but I think that adding some more utilities to JUnit will 
&gt;enhance it&#39;s out-of-the-box usability. The power users will eventually get 
&gt;under the hood and make extensions where it suits them.
&gt;
&gt;What&#39;s confusing to me about the assert class is that it only goes part 
&gt;of the way. It provides a bunch of assertions but then an arbitrary line 
&gt;in the sand has been drawn to say that these are all that anyone should 
&gt;need. This is confusing. I would rather see the Assert class simplified 
&gt;down to only one method: assertTrue. This would then beg for the 
&gt;extensibility you describe and the framework would at least be consistent. 
&gt;Otherwise, we should recognise the Assert class as a utility for 
&gt;programmers and load it up. You don&#39;t have to the methods there if you 
&gt;don&#39;t want to.
&gt;
&gt;Chris
&gt;
&gt;-----Original Message-----
&gt;From: Shane Celis
&gt;Sent: Friday, April 05, 2002 2:03 PM
&gt;To: junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt;Subject: Re: [junit] assertContains? -&gt; junit development question?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;I have to disagree.  I like the fact that the JUnit framework is itself
&gt;small, easy to comprehend, therefore making it easy to extend.  One
&gt;thing that perturbs me about the Assert class is the fact that it&#39;s
&gt;static.  If I want to override assertTrue() globally, for instance to
&gt;provide more verbose output, or to change it&#39;s behavior so that a
&gt;failure won&#39;t result in an exception being thrown thereby discontinuing
&gt;the rest of the test, I have to edit the JUnit Assert class itself.  If
&gt;Assert were an instance class I could avoid this, and easily add the
&gt;assert extensions that everyone is asking for.
&gt;
&gt;I do believe that they should be extensions to JUnit, without bloating
&gt;the original Assert class.
&gt;
&gt;-shane
&gt;
&gt;p.s.  Yes, I could make my own base TestCase class, but this doesn&#39;t
&gt;work retroactively, and certainly isn&#39;t a solution I would want to
&gt;foster for Assert Extension classes.
&gt;
&gt;On Friday, April 5, 2002, at 11:42  AM, Chris Eppstein wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; So your argument is that we really don&#39;t need anything other than
&gt; &gt; assertTrue? I&#39;d have to disagree.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; JUnit is a TESTING FRAMEWORK. By using it, testing should be made
&gt; &gt; easier. I&#39;d like to not have to reinvent the wheel for many of these
&gt; &gt; assertions. I understand that I can easily write my own assertion
&gt; &gt; library in just a couple hours but why should I have to? Certainly,
&gt; &gt; after years of use, we have identified many assertions that would be
&gt; &gt; useful to the community at large. As they are identified, it seems
&gt; &gt; natural for JUnit to provide them in future releases.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; -Chris
&gt; &gt;
